nterpersonal drawbacks noted, or if A\u2019s \u201cshow\u2011off\u201d behavior is shown to significantly undermine crew safety, I would reassess.\nMETADATA_JSON:\n{\"agent\": \"agent_2\", \"vote\": \"Candidate A\"}", "thoughts": "We have gathered info from Agent1 and Agent3 about teamwork/communication. Now we need to produce our public message: state current preferred candidate, summarize evidence, including from others, major alternatives, tradeoffs, uncertainties, what would change vote.\n\nWe need to consider all candidate info we have (our own). Let's list our own info (Agent2's subset). The problem statement gave a list of all candidate attributes, but each agent has a subset. We need to infer which subset we have. The initial description says \"Information available to you:\" then lists many bullet points. That is likely the full set for each agent? Actually each agent holds a different subset. But we as Agent2 have the list given under \"Information available to you:\"? Probably yes. So we have all those bullet points. Let's enumerate:\n\nCandidate A:\n- can anticipate dangerous situations.\n- able to see complex connections.\n- excellent spatial vision.\n- very good leadership qualities.\n- regarded as a show-off.\n- regarded as being not open to new ideas.\n\nCandidate B:\n- very conscientious.\n- handles stress very well.\n- good at assessing weather conditions.\n- excellent computer skills.\n- relatively weak memory for numbers.\n- makes nasty remarks about his colleagues.\n\nCandidate C:\n- can make correct decisions quickly.\n- difficulty communicating ideas.\n- regarded as egocentric.\n- not very willing to further his education.\n- keeps calm in a crisis.\n- understands complicated technology.\n\nCandidate D:\n- responds to unexpected events adequately.\n- can concentrate very well.\n- solves problems extremely well.\n- takes responsibility seriously.\n- regarded as a know-it-all.\n- has a hot temper.\n\nAlso earlier we saw \"Candidate D is regarded as a know-it-all.\" and \"hot temper\". Also earlier \"Candidate D is considered moody\" and \"loner\"? Wait those were from Agent3's info. Actually Agent3's info included \"Considered moody\" and \"Regarded as a loner\". But those were not in the original list. So Agent3 had extra info. So we have not that. Our own info does not include those. So we only have the above.\n\nNow evaluate each candidate for long-distance pilot role based on criteria.\n\nWe need to weigh strengths and weaknesses.\n\nCandidate A: strengths: anticipates dangerous situations (reliability, judgment), sees complex connections (cognitive), excellent spatial vision (technical), very good leadership (teamwork). Weaknesses: show-off (could affect crew morale), not open to new ideas (resistance to learning, adaptability). No explicit teamwork communication, but leadership suggests some. Show-off may be a concern for crew cooperation.\n\nCandidate B: strengths: very conscientious (reliability), handles stress well (calm under pressure), good at assessing weather (technical), excellent computer skills (technical). Weaknesses: weak memory for numbers (could affect navigation), makes nasty remarks (teamwork/communication negative). Overall good stress handling, but interpersonal issues.\n\nCandidate C: strengths: makes correct decisions quickly (judgment), keeps calm in crisis (calmness), understands complicated technology (technical). Weaknesses: difficulty communicating ideas (teamwork), egocentric (crew cooperation), not willing to further education (development). So communication issues.\n\nCandidate D: strengths: responds to unexpected events adequately (judgment), concentrates well (cognitive), solves problems extremely well (technical/cognitive), takes responsibility seriously (reliability). Weaknesses: hot temper (teamwork/communication), know-it-all (could affect crew dynamics). No explicit teamwork but temper and know-it-all are concerns.\n\nNow compare. Which candidate balances strengths